          "body": "Jeremiah 50 cannot be read in isolation from the book's structure. Chapters 30-33 are the 'Book of Consolation' — the restoration promises, the new covenant, the return from exile. But those promises were conditioned on a question the rest of the book left unanswered: if Babylon is God's servant of judgment, how can Israel be restored while Babylon stands? Chapter 50 answers the question structurally by placing the Babylon Oracle at the climax of the foreign-nation section and the conclusion of the entire prophetic corpus. The fall of Babylon is the hinge on which every restoration promise turns. The New Testament writers recognized this and applied the Babylon imagery eschatologically: Revelation 17-18 draws directly on Jeremiah 50-51 for the fall of 'Babylon the Great,' the archetypal city of human arrogance against God. The historical Babylon fell in 539 BC; the prophetic template remains active for every human empire that sets itself against the Holy One of Israel and holds God's people in captivity. The chapter is not a museum piece — it is a theological grammar for how God governs history."
